<subSubSection lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="382" pageId="9" pageNumber="380" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1656,2044]" pageId="9" pageNumber="380">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,461,1800,1827]" pageId="9" pageNumber="380">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
This new species is close to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Levander" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[779,913,1802,1828]" class="Eurotatoria" family="Lepadellidae" genus="Squatinella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ploima" pageId="9" pageNumber="380" phylum="Rotifera" rank="species" species="variegata">
<emphasis box="[779,913,1802,1828]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="380">S. variegata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as it shares with it a foot made up of two basal foot pseudosegments and a third element consisting of the fused third foot pseudosegment and the toes. The two differ by the rather rigid dorsal spine, which is variable in length but always straight in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Levander" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[1133,1268,1874,1900]" class="Eurotatoria" family="Lepadellidae" genus="Squatinella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ploima" pageId="9" pageNumber="380" phylum="Rotifera" rank="species" species="variegata">
<emphasis box="[1133,1268,1874,1900]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="380">S. variegata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and relatively short and weakly but clearly and consistently S-shaped in 
<taxonomicName authority="Luo &amp; Segers, 2020" authorityName="Luo &amp; Segers" authorityYear="2020" box="[795,925,1910,1936]" class="Eurotatoria" family="Lepadellidae" genus="Squatinella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ploima" pageId="9" pageNumber="380" phylum="Rotifera" rank="species" species="curviseta" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[795,925,1910,1936]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="380">S. curviseta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[931,993,1910,1936]" pageId="9" pageNumber="380">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[931,993,1910,1936]" pageId="9" pageNumber="380" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
This peculiar spine shape may be adaptive: in swimming specimens the spine is bent posteriad, along the longitudinal axis of the body; in 
<taxonomicName authority="Luo &amp; Segers, 2020" authorityName="Luo &amp; Segers" authorityYear="2020" box="[1275,1407,1946,1972]" class="Eurotatoria" family="Lepadellidae" genus="Squatinella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ploima" pageId="9" pageNumber="380" phylum="Rotifera" rank="species" species="curviseta" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1275,1407,1946,1972]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="380">S. curviseta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="380">
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="9" pageNumber="380" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
this S-shaped spine will fit snugly over the body and foot, possibly resulting in reduced drag when the animal glides over a surface.
</paragraph>
